    "ancestors": [
        {
            "code": "pt-PT",
            "role": "superstrate",
            "weight": 0.75,
            "notes": "European Portuguese superstrate: colonial contact from 1460s. The lexifier. Vocabulary, much of morphology and some phonology derive from 15th–17th century Portuguese."
        }
    ],
    "notes": "Kabuverdianu / Cape Verdean Creole (ALUPEC orthography). Portuguese-based creole; vernacular language of Cape Verde (~600,000 speakers). Two macro-dialects: Badiu (Santiago island, Sotavento group) and Sampadjudo (Barlavento islands). KEY FEATURES: (1) NASAL VOWELS: ã/ẽ/ĩ/õ/ũ are phonemic, from African substrate influence and retention of archaic PT nasality. (2) FIVE-VOWEL SYSTEM: no /ɨ/; unstressed vowels preserved. (3) SILENT H: <h> has no phonetic value. (4) AFFRICATES: tx=[tʃ], dj=[dʒ] — innovations relative to PT. (5) WORD-FINAL WEAKENING: final obstruents may be deleted, especially in Badiu variety. (6) SIBILANT: x=[ʃ], j=[ʒ], s=[s]. (7) RHOTIC: alveolar [r] throughout. Official orthography ALUPEC (Alfabeto Unificado para a Escrita do Cabo-Verdiano) adopted 1998, revised 2009.",
